The URL is unquoted and contains an ampersand (`&amp;`); so the shell reads that line as:
&lt;pre&gt;
&lt;code&gt;curl -D $HEADERS_FILE_NAME -o $FILE --fail http://&lt;SOMEURLHERE&gt;:7001/articles?indexingInfoId=4 &lt;/code&gt;&lt;b&gt;&amp;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;code&gt; format=xml 2&gt;/dev/null&lt;/code&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;
and thus runs `curl` at the background. Since `format=xml 2&gt;/dev/null` is a valid command line you&#39;re not getting an error from it.

See  
[Bash Reference Manual &#167; Quoting](https://www.gnu.org/software/bash/manual/html_node/Quoting.html) and,  
[Bash Reference Manual &#167; Lists](https://www.gnu.org/software/bash/manual/html_node/Lists.html#Lists)  
for further information.

